'''Avril Dannica Haines''' (born August 29, 1969) is an American lawyer who is the current [[Deputy Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]]. Haines previously served in [[Office of the White House Counsel]] as the Deputy Assistant and Deputy Counsel to the President for National Security Affairs in the administration of [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] from 2010 to 2013, before being nominated deputy director of the CIA and becoming the first woman to hold the position.

==Early life and education==
Haines was born in [[New York City]]'s [[Manhattan]] borough on August 29, 1969, to parents Adrian ([[n<U+00E9>e]] Rappin) and Dr. Thomas Haines.<ref name ="Klaidman13">{{cite web | url=http://mag.newsweek.com/2013/06/26/avril-haines-the-least-likely-spy.html | title =The Least Likely Spy | author =Daniel Klaidman | author2 =''[[Newsweek]]'' | publisher =newsweek.com | date =June 26, 2013}}</ref> Her mother, Adrian, was a painter. Adrian developed [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]] and contracted avian [[tuberculosis]], passing away when Haines was only fifteen years old.<ref name ="Klaidman13"/> Her father, Thomas, is a biochemist and professor emeritus at [[Rockefeller University]] who helped found the [[City University of New York]] medical school, where he served as the chair of the biochemistry department.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://observer.com/2008/07/serious-chemistry/ | title =Serious Chemistry | author =Dana Rubinstein | author2 =''[[New York Observer]]'' | publisher =observer.com | date =July 15, 2008}}</ref> After graduating from [[Hunter College High School]], Haines traveled to [[Japan]] for a year and enrolled in [[Kodokan]], an elite [[judo]] institute in [[Tokyo]].<ref name ="Klaidman13"/> In 1988, Haines enrolled in the [[University of Chicago]] where she studied [[theoretical physics]]. While attending the University of Chicago, Haines worked repairing car engines at a mechanic shop in [[Hyde Park, Chicago|Hyde Park]].<ref name ="Klaidman13"/> In 1991 Haines had taken up flying lessons in [[New Jersey]], where she met her future husband, David Davighi. She later graduated with her [[Bachelors of Arts]] in [[physics]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mag.uchicago.edu/university-news/notes-4%20 | title =The University of Chicago Magazine | author =Katherine Muhlenkamp | author2 =''[[University of Chicago Press]]'' | publisher =uchicago.edu | year =2013}}</ref>

In 1992, Haines moved to [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] where she enrolled as a [[Doctorate of philosophy|doctorate student]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]]. However, later that year, Haines dropped out at Johns Hopkins, and alongside her future husband, purchased an auctioned bar in [[Fell's Point, Baltimore]] which had been seized in a drug raid;<ref name ="Klaidman13"/> turning the former bar into an independent bookstore and caf<U+00E9>.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-01-09/features/1994009208_1_bookstore-cafe-world-cafe-vegetarian-cafe | title =Food and coffee, with books, billiards and student chefs | author =Mary Corey | author2 =''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' | publisher =baltimoresun.com | date =January 9, 1994}}</ref> She named the store, Adrian's Book Cafe, after her late mother; Adrian's realistic oil paintings filled the store.<ref>http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-01-09/features/1994009208_1_bookstore-cafe-world-cafe-vegetarian-cafe</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2341008/Avril-Haines-President-Obamas-pick-CIAs-second-command-held-erotica-nights-Baltimore-bookstore.html | title =President Obama's pick for the CIA's second-in-command once held erotica nights at her Baltimore bookstore | author =''[[Daily Mail]]'' | publisher =dailymail.co.uk | date =June 13, 2013}}</ref> The bookstore won City Paper's "Best Independent Bookstore" in 1997 and was known for having an unusual collection of literary offerings, local writers, and small press publications.<ref>http://blogs.citypaper.com/index.php/the-news-hole/new-cia-number-two-was-once-a-fells-point-fixture/</ref>  Adrian's hosted a number of literary readings, including erotica readings, which suddenly became a media focus when she was appointed by the President to be the Deputy Director of the CIA.<ref>http://mediamatters.org/print/blog/2013/06/14/erotica-high-heels-and-handbags-is-this-how-the/194471</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-05-22/features/1995142103_1_romp-haines-fells | title =Between The Covers Erotica Nights A Hot Item At Fells Point Bookstore | author =Mary Corey | author2 =''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' | publisher =baltimoresun.com | date =May 22, 1995}}</ref> She served as the president of the Fell's Point Business Association until 1998,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1998-01-04/news/1998004073_1_fells-point-benefits-district-additional-tax | title =Fells Point debates tax to add desired services Benefits: Homeowners and merchants want a safer, cleaner neighborhood. But some residents don't think they can afford a community district levy. | author =Brenda J. Buote | author2 =''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' | publisher =baltimoresun.com | date =January 4, 1998}}</ref> when she enrolled at the [[Georgetown University Law Center]]. Haines later received her [[Juris Doctor]] from Georgetown in 2001.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/reliable-source/wp/2013/06/13/avril-haines-new-cia-2-ran-indie-bookstore-remembered-for-90s-erotica-nights/ | title =Avril Haines, new CIA #2, ran indie bookstore remembered for <U+2019>90s <U+2018>erotica nights<U+2019> | author =Roxanne Roberts, Emily Yahr | author2 =''[[Washington Post]]'' | publisher =washingtonpost.com | date =June 13, 2013}}</ref>

==Career ==
From 2001 until 2002, Haines was a legal officer at The [[Hague Conference on Private International Law]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cjicl.org.uk/2013/04/23/international-law-a-mans-world-2/ | title =International Law: A Man<U+2019>s World? | author =Naomi Burke | author2 =''[[Cambridge University Press]]'', Cambridge Journal of International and Comparative Law | publisher =cjicl.org.uk | date =April 23, 2013}}</ref>  From 2002 until 2003, she served as a law clerk for [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] Judge [[Danny Julian Boggs]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.mcclatchydc.com/washington/2013/06/changes-at-the-cia-.html | title =Changes at the CIA | author =Lesley Clark | author2 =''[[McClatchy News Service]]'' | publisher =mcclatchydc.com | date =June 12, 2013}}</ref>

From 2003 until 2006, Haines worked in the Office of the [[Legal Adviser of the Department of State]], first in the Office of Treaty Affairs and then in the Office of Political Military Affairs.<ref name ="WHOPS">{{cite web | url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/04/17/president-obama-announces-more-key-administration-posts | title =President Obama Announces More Key Administration Posts | author =''[[White House Office of the Press Secretary]]'' | publisher =whitehouse.gov | date =April 17, 2013}}</ref>

From 2007 until 2008, Haines worked for the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]] as Deputy Chief Counsel for the Majority [[United States Senate|Senate]] [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] (under then-chairman [[Joe Biden]]).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2013/06/12/191061035/cia-deputy-director-michael-morell-retires | title =CIA Deputy Director Michael Morell Retires | author =Eyder Peralta | author2 =''[[National Public Radio]]'' | publisher =npr.org | date =June 12, 2013}}</ref>  She then worked for the State Department as the assistant legal adviser for treaty affairs from 2008 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/10117458/Avril-Haines-appointed-first-female-CIA-deputy-director.html | title =Avril Haines appointed first female CIA deputy director | author =Bonnie Malkin | author2 =''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' | publisher =telegraph.co.uk | date =June 13, 2013}}</ref>

In 2010, Haines was appointed to serve in the office of the [[White House Counsel]] as Deputy Assistant to the President and Deputy Counsel to the President for National Security Affairs at the White House.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-06-13/news/39954613_1_cia-michael-morell-benghazi | title =CIA deputy director retires | author =Kimberly Dozier | author2 =[[Associated Press]] | publisher =''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' | date =June 13, 2013}}</ref>

On April 18, 2013, Obama nominated Haines to serve as [[Legal Adviser of the Department of State]], to fill the position vacated after [[Harold Hongju Koh]] resigned to return to teaching at [[Yale Law School]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/04/18/presidential-nominations-sent-senate | title =Presidential Nominations Sent to the Senate | author =''[[White House Office of the Press Secretary]]'' | publisher =whitehouse.gov | date =April 18, 2013}}</ref> However, on June 13, 2013, Obama withdrew Haines' nomination to be Legal Adviser of the Department of State, choosing instead to select her as [[Deputy Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/13/us/cia-to-get-first-woman-in-no-2-job.html?_r=1& | title =C.I.A. to Get First Woman in No. 2 Job | author =Scott Shane | author2 =''[[New York Times]]'' | publisher =nytimes.com | date =June 12, 2013}}</ref>  Haines was nominated to replace [[Michael Morell]], the CIA's deputy and former acting director. The office of the deputy director is not subject to Senate confirmation, with Haines subsequently taking office on August 9, 2013, the final day of Morrell's tenure.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-06-12/world/39918735_1_brennan-s-haines-cia-s | title =CIA<U+2019>s deputy director to be replaced with White House lawyer | author =Karen DeYoung, Greg Miller | author2 =''[[Washington Post]]'' | publisher =washingtonpost.com | date =June 12, 2013}}</ref> Haines has become first woman to ever hold the office of the deputy director, making her the highest ranking woman in the CIA's history.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/DC-Decoder/2013/0613/Why-Obama-chose-woman-with-no-CIA-experience-for-No.-2-CIA-job | title =Why Obama chose woman with no CIA experience for No. 2 CIA job | author =Jennifer Skalka Tulumello | author2 =''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'' | publisher =csmonitor.com | date =June 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/new-cia-deputy-avril-haines-hosted-erotica-readings-90s-article-1.1372072 | title =New CIA deputy Avril Haines hosted erotica readings in the <U+2019>90s | author =Adam Edelman | author2 =''[[New York Daily News]]'' | publisher =nydailynews.com | date =June 13, 2013}}</ref>

